The PAS Premium

{r setup,echo=FALSE,message=FALSE} library(ggplot2) library(dplyr) library(leaflet) library(RColorBrewer) library(lubridate) library(pander) library(reshape) library(leaflet) library(rgdal) library(foreign) library(survival)

Background & Timeline

  • Sadie Tanner Mossell Alexander - envisanged in 1998, completed in 2001
  • 500 students
  • $1330 per student from UPenn
  • At capacity by 2011, 2013 winter debacle, lotteries conducted but no denials in 2014, 2015, 2016

PAS Premium Heuristics and Previous Studies

  • A $100k premium
  • In fact, prices of homes can jump $50,000 or even $100,000 if theyre in the Penn Alexander catchmenteven if theyre exactly the same kind of homes as the non-catchment homes across the street. Curbed 1/16/13
  • Penn Urban Research
  • No pricing models I could find

Questions

  • Is there really a catchment premium?
  • Did it exist before the school was built?
  • Does it affect rentals?

Analysis strategy

  • Focus on border properties
  • Linear regression & conditional logistic regression modeling
  • Use Philadelphia Office of Property Assessment API and Casey Thomas PHL-opa wrapper
  • Statistics and visualization in R with Leaflet for mapping

Is there really a catchment premium?

Price per square foot

{r, echo=FALSE} test_decade<-function(adecade){ props %>% filter(catchment_side == 'inside', decade == adecade) %>% select(adj_price_sqft) %>% collect %>% .[["adj_price_sqft"]] -> inside props %>% filter(catchment_side == 'outside', decade == adecade) %>% select(adj_price_sqft) %>% collect %>% .[["adj_price_sqft"]] -> outside testres<-wilcox.test(inside,outside) #testres<-t.test(, props %>% filter(catchment_side == 'outside', decade == adecade) %>% select(adj_price_sqft)) return(round(testres$p.value,2)) } props %>% group_by(decade,catchment_side) %>% summarize(meanprice=mean(adj_price_sqft)) %>% cast(decade~catchment_side) -> premium_tab premium_tab$wilcox.test.pval<-sapply(premium_tab$decade,test_decade) knitr::kable(premium_tab)

Can we model it?

class: small-code {r, echo=TRUE} model<-lm(adj_price ~ sqft + in_catchment*pas_era + type + caseshiller + clust, data=props) summary(model)

What does this say?

2000sqft residence inside the catchment in cluster 8 in 2016 {r, echo=FALSE} attach(as.list(model$coefficients)) ``{r, echo=TRUE}(Intercept)+2000*sqft+in_catchmentTRUE+pas_eraTRUE+typeRESIDENCE+188.24*caseshiller+clust8+in_catchmentTRUE:pas_eraTRUE`

```

2000sqft residence outside the catchment in cluster 2 in 2016 {r, echo=TRUE} `(Intercept)`+2000*sqft+typeRESIDENCE+188.24*caseshiller+clust2

The PAS premium is the sum of the catchment and era (>=2001) regressors and their interaction {r, echo=TRUE} in_catchmentTRUE+pas_eraTRUE+`in_catchmentTRUE:pas_eraTRUE` {r, echo=FALSE} detach()

Assumption problems

{r, echo=TRUE} model<-lm(adj_price ~ sqft + in_catchment*pas_era + type + caseshiller + clust, data=props) resids<-resid(model) shapiro.test(resids)

Can this be modeled differently to get on better statistical footing?

Using conditional logistic regression we can place each sale in a strata of comparable properties {r, echo=TRUE} summary(clogit(in_catchment ~ adj_price + sqft + pas_era + type + caseshiller + strata(clust) , props))
